Dataset Description:

The machine_temperature_system_failure.csv dataset is part of the Numenta Anomaly Benchmark (NAB), designed for testing time-series anomaly detection models. It contains temperature readings from an industrial machine over time, with a recorded system failure event that presents as an anomaly in the data. The key variables include a timestamp and a single numeric feature value, which represents the machine’s temperature at each recorded time point.

Source: NAB kaggle

Not Applicable¶

There is no explicit class label in this dataset. The autoencoder model will learn to reconstruct normal behavior, and anomalies will be inferred based on reconstruction error. Therefore, addressing class imbalance is not applicable at this preprocessing stage.

Model 1 Architecture¶

In [ ]:
import torch.nn as nn

class DenseAutoencoder(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, input_dim=50, hidden_dims=[32, 16], bottleneck_dim=8, dropout=0.0):
        super(DenseAutoencoder, self).__init__()

        # Encoder
        self.encoder = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(input_dim, hidden_dims[0]),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Dropout(dropout),
            nn.Linear(hidden_dims[0], hidden_dims[1]),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Dropout(dropout),
            nn.Linear(hidden_dims[1], bottleneck_dim)
        )

        # Decoder
        self.decoder = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(bottleneck_dim, hidden_dims[1]),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Dropout(dropout),
            nn.Linear(hidden_dims[1], hidden_dims[0]),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Dropout(dropout),
            nn.Linear(hidden_dims[0], input_dim),
            nn.Sigmoid()
        )

    def forward(self, x):
        encoded = self.encoder(x)
        decoded = self.decoder(encoded)
        return decoded

Model 2 Architecture¶

In [ ]:
import torch.nn as nn

class LSTMAutoencoder(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, input_dim=1, hidden_dim=32, bottleneck_dim=16, num_layers=1, seq_len=50, dropout=0.0):
        super(LSTMAutoencoder, self).__init__()
        self.seq_len = seq_len
        self.hidden_dim = hidden_dim

        # Encoder
        self.encoder_lstm = nn.LSTM(
            input_size=input_dim,
            hidden_size=hidden_dim,
            num_layers=num_layers,
            dropout=dropout if num_layers > 1 else 0.0,
            batch_first=True
        )

        self.bottleneck = nn.Linear(hidden_dim, bottleneck_dim)

        # Decoder
        self.decoder_lstm = nn.LSTM(
            input_size=bottleneck_dim,
            hidden_size=hidden_dim,
            num_layers=num_layers,
            dropout=dropout if num_layers > 1 else 0.0,
            batch_first=True
        )

        self.output_layer = nn.Linear(hidden_dim, input_dim)

    def forward(self, x):
        batch_size = x.size(0)

        # Encoder
        _, (h_n, _) = self.encoder_lstm(x)  # h_n: [num_layers, B, hidden_dim]
        h_last = h_n[-1]  # [B, hidden_dim]
        bottleneck_out = self.bottleneck(h_last)  # [B, bottleneck_dim]
        bottleneck_seq = bottleneck_out.unsqueeze(1).repeat(1, self.seq_len, 1)  # [B, seq_len, bottleneck_dim]

        # Decoder
        decoded, _ = self.decoder_lstm(bottleneck_seq)
        out = self.output_layer(decoded)
        return out

Model 3 Architecture¶

In [ ]:
import torch.nn as nn

class Conv1DAutoencoder(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, input_channels=1, conv_channels=[16, 8], seq_len=50, dropout=0.0):
        super(Conv1DAutoencoder, self).__init__()

        self.encoder = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Conv1d(input_channels, conv_channels[0], kernel_size=3, padding=1),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Dropout(dropout),
            nn.Conv1d(conv_channels[0], conv_channels[1], kernel_size=3, padding=1),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Dropout(dropout)
        )

        self.decoder = nn.Sequential(
            nn.ConvTranspose1d(conv_channels[1], conv_channels[0], kernel_size=3, padding=1),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Dropout(dropout),
            nn.ConvTranspose1d(conv_channels[0], input_channels, kernel_size=3, padding=1),
            nn.Sigmoid()
        )

    def forward(self, x):
        encoded = self.encoder(x)
        decoded = self.decoder(encoded)
        return decoded

Training Loop

In [ ]:
import torch
import torch.nn as nn
from torch.utils.data import DataLoader, TensorDataset
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pickle
# for reproducibility in DataLoader
g = torch.Generator()
g.manual_seed(SEED)


def train_model(model,
                train_data,
                val_data,
                loss_fn,
                optimizer,
                num_epochs=20,
                batch_size=32,
                device=device,
                save_path=None):

    model.to(device)

    # Prepare PyTorch DataLoaders for training and validation
    train_loader = DataLoader(TensorDataset(torch.tensor(train_data, dtype=torch.float32)),
                              batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=True, generator=g)
    val_loader = DataLoader(TensorDataset(torch.tensor(val_data, dtype=torch.float32)),
                            batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=False)

    train_losses = []
    val_losses = []

    best_val_loss = float('inf')
    best_model_state = None

    for epoch in range(num_epochs):
        model.train()
        running_train_loss = 0.0

        for batch in train_loader:
            inputs = batch[0].to(device)

            # Adjust input shape
            if isinstance(model, DenseAutoencoder):
                pass
            if isinstance(model, LSTMAutoencoder):
                inputs = inputs.unsqueeze(-1)
            elif isinstance(model, Conv1DAutoencoder):
                inputs = inputs.unsqueeze(1)

            outputs = model(inputs)
            loss = loss_fn(outputs, inputs)

            optimizer.zero_grad()
            loss.backward()
            optimizer.step()
            running_train_loss += loss.item()

        avg_train_loss = running_train_loss / len(train_loader)
        train_losses.append(avg_train_loss)

        # Evaluate on validation set
        model.eval()
        running_val_loss = 0.0
        with torch.no_grad():
            for batch in val_loader:
                inputs = batch[0].to(device)

                if isinstance(model, LSTMAutoencoder):
                    inputs = inputs.unsqueeze(-1)
                elif isinstance(model, Conv1DAutoencoder):
                    inputs = inputs.unsqueeze(1)

                outputs = model(inputs)
                loss = loss_fn(outputs, inputs)
                running_val_loss += loss.item()

        avg_val_loss = running_val_loss / len(val_loader)
        val_losses.append(avg_val_loss)

        # Checkpoint best model
        if avg_val_loss < best_val_loss:
            best_val_loss = avg_val_loss
            best_model_state = model.state_dict().copy()

        print(f"Epoch {epoch+1}/{num_epochs} | Train Loss: {avg_train_loss:.4f} | Val Loss: {avg_val_loss:.4f}")

    # Load best model weights
    model.load_state_dict(best_model_state)

    # Save model and metadata
    if save_path:
        # Save model weights (.pt)
        torch.save(model.state_dict(), save_path)
        print(f"Best model weights saved to: {save_path}")

        # Save training metadata (.pkl)
        metadata = {
            'train_losses': train_losses,
            'val_losses': val_losses,
            'best_val_loss': best_val_loss,
            'num_epochs': num_epochs,
            'batch_size': batch_size,
            'optimizer': optimizer.__class__.__name__,
            'loss_fn': loss_fn.__class__.__name__,
        }

        meta_path = save_path.replace('.pt', '.pkl')
        with open(meta_path, 'wb') as f:
            pickle.dump(metadata, f)
        print(f"Training metadata saved to: {meta_path}")

    # Plot training/validation loss curves
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
    plt.plot(train_losses, label='Train Loss')
    plt.plot(val_losses, label='Validation Loss')
    plt.title(f"Training vs. Validation Loss: {save_path}")
    plt.xlabel("Epoch")
    plt.ylabel("Loss")
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    return model, train_losses, val_losses

Among the five DenseAutoencoder variants tested, Experiment 05 delivered the best performance. Its architecture used three hidden layers [128, 64, 32] before the bottleneck, paired with moderate dropout and a reduced learning rate. This configuration produced the lowest and most stable validation loss, with train and validation curves tightly aligned throughout training, which is a strong indicator of good generalization without overfitting.

By comparison:

  • Exp 01 & 02 underperformed due to reduced capacity or excessive dropout.

  • Exp 03 was stable but slightly less expressive.

  • Exp 04 showed minor improvement in capacity, but plateaued earlier.

  • Exp 05 balanced depth, regularization, and optimization, making it the most robust choice for downstream evaluation.

Evaluated three LSTM autoencoder variants. All models produced nearly flat, linear-like loss curves with minimal progression, indicating that learning stalled early. While the first model achieved the lowest and most stable validation loss, its curve still lacked the smooth, rounded descent seen in well-optimized training. Overall, although none of the LSTM models were particularly strong, the first was the least problematic and is the only one retained for final evaluation.

After systematically training and tuning variations of each architecture, compared their performance based on training and validation loss trends:

  • Conv1D Autoencoder (Experiment 3) performed well, with smooth convergence and low final loss, but still slightly behind Dense (Exp 5) in overall consistency and final validation performance.

Therefore, Dense Autoencoder Experiment 5 is selected as the overall best model due to its optimal balance of convergence speed, validation loss minimization, and training stability.

from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error, r2_score
import numpy as np

def compute_regression_metrics(model, data, device):
    model.eval()
    model.to(device)

    inputs = torch.tensor(data, dtype=torch.float32).to(device)
    with torch.no_grad():
        outputs = model(inputs)

    inputs_np = inputs.cpu().numpy()
    outputs_np = outputs.cpu().numpy()

    mae = mean_absolute_error(inputs_np, outputs_np)
    rmse = mean_squared_error(inputs_np, outputs_np) ** 0.5
    r2 = r2_score(inputs_np, outputs_np)

    return mae, rmse, r2

Final Model Architecture: Dense vs. LSTM Comparison

While I experimented with both Dense and LSTM autoencoder architectures, the best performance was achieved using a DenseAutoencoder. Below is a comparison of the two configurations:

Feature DenseAutoencoder LSTMAutoencoder
Input Shape Flat vector of 50 values Sequence of 50 timesteps × 1 feature
Encoder Layers 3 Linear layers: 128 → 64 → 32 1 LSTM layer (hidden size = 64), followed by linear → 32 bottleneck
Bottleneck Dimension 16 32
Decoder Layers 3 Linear layers: 32 → 64 → 128 Linear → LSTM (hidden size = 64), output shape (50, 1)
Activation ReLU + Sigmoid (final layer) Implicit (tanh in LSTM), output passed directly
Dropout Rate 0.3 (between dense layers) 0.3 (applied in LSTM)
Optimizer Adam (learning rate = 0.0005) Adam (learning rate = 0.001)
Batch Size 64 64
Epochs Trained 30 30

Dense Performed Better

  • The DenseAutoencoder was better suited for the fixed-length, flat windowed input used in this task (50-timestep temperature segments). Since I was not modeling long-range temporal dependencies, a deep feedforward network was more effective and efficient.
  • The LSTM struggled to learn meaningful sequential representations, likely due to limited temporal complexity in the machine temperature data.
  • Dense architecture also provided more stable training curves and lower reconstruction losses on both validation and test sets.

Reconstruction Error Distribution

The reconstruction error histogram shows that most test samples are reconstructed with very low error, concentrated near 0. This indicates that the autoencoder successfully learned to represent the dominant patterns in the data. However, the right-skewed tail in the distribution reveals that a minority of samples exhibit higher reconstruction errors.

These cases may correspond to rare or anomalous patterns that the model failed to reconstruct accurately. To identify such anomalies, applied a threshold based on the 95th percentile of reconstruction errors, resulting in a cutoff of approximately 0.0236. Using this threshold, the model flagged 170 out of 3397 test samples as potential anomalies.

  • The dense autoencoder outperformed all other architectures (LSTM and Conv1D) both visually and quantitatively.
  • Hyperparameter tuning, particularly deepening the encoder path and reducing learning rate, helped the model improve stability and final accuracy.
  • The R² score of 0.9166 confirms that the model explains over 91% of variance in the test data.
  • Anomalies were identified consistently based on reconstruction error. Most errors remained low, with only a few samples exceeding the chosen threshold.
  • Challenges included distinguishing architectures with subtle loss differences and selecting appropriate hyperparameters for a small bottleneck dimension.
  • Discuss the strengths and limitations of using autoencoders for anomaly detection.

Strengths:

  • Unsupervised Learning: Autoencoders do not require labeled anomalies, making them ideal when only normal data is available during training.
  • Reconstruction-Based Detection: By learning to reconstruct normal patterns, autoencoders can naturally flag deviations as anomalies when reconstruction error is high.
  • Flexible Architectures: Autoencoders can be adapted to different data types (e.g., Dense for tabular, LSTM for sequences, Conv1D for signals).
  • Scalable and Efficient: Once trained, inference is fast and scalable to large datasets.
  • Anomaly Localization: In some applications (e.g., images or sequences), reconstruction error can be analyzed per feature or timestep to localize anomalous regions.

Limitations:

  • Dependence on Training Data Quality: If anomalous patterns appear in training data, the model may learn to reconstruct them, reducing anomaly sensitivity.
  • Threshold Selection: Choosing a suitable reconstruction error threshold is non-trivial and may require domain knowledge or heuristic methods (e.g., percentiles).
  • Limited Interpretability: Autoencoders provide limited insights into why a data point is considered anomalous.
  • Overfitting Risk: With excessive model capacity, autoencoders may overfit and reconstruct even anomalous samples well, leading to false negatives.
  • Sensitivity to Hyperparameters: Performance can vary significantly based on architecture depth, bottleneck size, and regularization, requiring careful tuning.
